&lt;h2 id="faqs-on-the-three-new-complementary-investments"&gt;FAQs on the three new complementary investments&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;h3 id="dsb-breakthrough-fund"&gt;
&lt;abbr title="Data Strategy Board"&gt;DSB&lt;/abbr&gt; Breakthrough Fund&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. What is the &lt;abbr title="Data Strategy Board"&gt;DSB&lt;/abbr&gt; Breakthrough Fund?
A. The fund will assist open data proposals where government departments, government agencies and local authorities have identified constraints on data release. It will help the government’s “presumption to publish” agenda.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. Who is eligible?
A. Government departments, government agencies and local authorities are eligible to apply. In the case of local authorities, collaborative bids will be encouraged (especially from district councils) based on geographic, economic, community of interest, shared services or other local or regional partnership groupings.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. What will the fund cover?
A. The fund will cover a number of sub-themes of activity which could include funding for:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;IT/tool development&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;standardising data&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;making data linkable&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;Q. What are the criteria for applications?
A. In order to qualify for funding organisations must:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;demonstrate that they have not been able to identify appropriate funding through existing budgets&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;commit to making the data available for free under the Open Government License, to high quality, with appropriate frequent updates on an ongoing basis&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;show that there is a demand for the data to be released / standardised / linked and that there is a longer term economic, social or environmental benefit to making it more accessible&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;commit to ways to track the use of their data and the benefit which has been realised from its release&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;make the data available through the government’s Data.gov.uk website&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h2 id="open-data-immersion-programme"&gt;Open Data Immersion programme&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;including competition prizes &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. What is the Open Data Immersion Programme?
A. The programme will comprise of a series of events and competitions, run by the Open Data Institute and NESTA (National Endowment for Science Technology &amp;amp; the Arts). It will involve a range of data owners – such as Trading Funds, Departments, agencies and local authorities - and data users.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The events will be aligned to both specific sector challenges and industry themes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. Who is eligible for the programme?
A. The programme will be targeted at small to medium enterprises (&lt;abbr title="small to medium enterprises"&gt;SMEs&lt;/abbr&gt;) and start-ups. Key participants will be developers who can code the products and services, data owners/domain experts who understand and can help source the appropriate information and product/industry business leaders who have an explicit understanding of the real world industry challenges.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. What will participants get from the events?
A. Participants who are selected to partake in an Innovation Camp event will get the opportunity to work closely with data owners/domain experts to help develop their products, and also the chance to partner with other
&lt;abbr title="small to medium enterprises"&gt;SMEs&lt;/abbr&gt;/start-ups.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The winning projects at each event will be eligible to take their concepts into early product development with pre-seed funding from the Technology Strategy Board (TSB) Innovation Vouchers or competition prizes run by NESTA.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ODI anticipates engaging the private sector to in some way match the commitment of the Data Strategy Board funding. This could be in the form of NESTA prizes, support and or resources to support the winning projects.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. Where can I find more information about the Open Data Immersion Programme?
A. More information on the programme will be published shortly on the Open Data Institute website at: www.theodi.org&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="open-geographical-data-upgrades"&gt;Open Geographical Data upgrades&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. What are Open Geographical updates?
A. The Open Geographical updates include new product releases; release of OS VectorMap District Version 1, and OS Terrain 50. New styling is being released for Meridian2 and Strategi. These updates will increase the quality, accuracy and currency of a number of products, whilst the styling will make them easier to use and interpret.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. Who is eligible?
A. The new products will be available to everybody through the &lt;a href="www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/oswebsite/products/os-opendata.html"&gt;OS OpenData website&lt;/a&gt; from April 2013.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. Where can I find more information about the new products?
A. Further information is available on the &lt;a href="www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk"&gt;Ordnance Survey website&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="faq-innovation-vouchers"&gt;FAQ Innovation Vouchers&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q.  How does this relate to the existing Innovation Vouchers programme?
A.  The Technology Strategy Board (TSB) will deliver the new vouchers as part of the existing Innovation Voucher programme.  The vouchers will also adopt the format and structure of the vouchers available to other sectors.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q.  How much is each voucher worth? 
A.   The vouchers will have a value of £5,000 each. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q.  How can I apply for a voucher?
A.  Application for the vouchers will be online through the existing TSB Vouchers portal at: https://vouchers.innovateuk.org/   &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q. What are Innovation Vouchers?
A. The purpose of Innovation Vouchers is to help stimulate and promote innovation in targeted sectors where we want to encourage greater levels of innovation. Vouchers can be used to incentivise &lt;abbr title="small to medium enterprises"&gt;SMEs&lt;/abbr&gt; to engage with the knowledge base and other forms of innovation advice to help them to grow by developing new ideas and potential new commercial products. Start-ups and small and medium sized businesses and sole traders from across the UK can apply for an Innovation Voucher. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q.  Who is eligible?
A.   Innovation Vouchers for Open Data Business Innovators and Inventors are aimed at &lt;abbr title="small to medium enterprises"&gt;SMEs&lt;/abbr&gt; and sole traders. The vouchers will help them access specialist and technical advice from knowledge suppliers to help develop new or improve existing data products that make use of open data.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Q.  Where can I find more information?
A.  Further details can be found on the &lt;a rel="external" href="https://vouchers.innovateuk.org"&gt;TSB website&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="data-strategy-board-members"&gt;Data Strategy Board members&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;h3 id="stephan-shakespeare-chair-dsb"&gt;Stephan Shakespeare: Chair, &lt;abbr title="Data Strategy Board"&gt;DSB&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stephan Shakespeare is CEO and Co-founder of YouGov, the international market research agency. He has been a school-teacher, writer and campaigner, and founded PoliticsHome.com. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stephan is sits on the Public Policy External Advisory Board of the University of Cambridge, he is co-founder of Opigram, sat on the LSE’s Polis Advisory Board and is a former Justice of the Peace. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stephan studied English at Oxford. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Twitter: @StephanShaxper  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="nick-baldwin-chair-public-weather-service-customer-group-pwscg"&gt;Nick Baldwin: Chair, Public Weather Service Customer Group (PWSCG)&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nick Baldwin has been independent Chairman of the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/about-us/what/pws/customer-group"&gt;Public Weather Service Customer Group (PWSCG)&lt;/a&gt; since September 2007. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He has a portfolio of advisory, consultancy and governance roles, working in the government, utility, housing and charity sectors. He is Chairman of the Office for Nuclear Regulation, Chairman of Sanctuary Housing Group and Chairman of Ambitious About Autism. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Previously he worked in electricity, gas and water utilities, culminating in being the Chief Executive of Powergen plc. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nick is a Chartered Engineer, a Chartered Director, a Fellow of the Institution of Engineering &amp;amp; Technology (FIET) and a Fellow of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers (FIMechE). &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="professor-sir-john-beddington-government-chief-scientific-adviser"&gt;Professor Sir John Beddington: Government Chief Scientific Adviser&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sir John Beddington was appointed as &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.bis.gov.uk/go-science/chief-scientific-adviser"&gt;Government Chief Scientific Adviser (GCSA)&lt;/a&gt; on 1 January 2008. Since being in post, the GCSA has led on providing scientific advice to government during the 2009 swine flu outbreak and the 2010 volcanic ash incident. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The GCSA has also been responsible for increasing the scientific capacity across Whitehall by encouraging all major departments of state to recruit a Chief Scientific Adviser. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Throughout 2008 and 2009 Sir John raised the concept of the ‘Perfect Storm’ of food, energy and water security in the context of climate change, gaining considerable media attention and raising this as a priority in the UK and internationally. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Prior to his appointment as GCSA, he was Professor of Applied Population Biology and headed the main departments of environmental science and technology at Imperial College. His main research interests are the application of biological and economic analysis to problems of Natural Resource Management. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sir John has previously been advisor to a number of UK government departments including the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, the Ministry of Defence and the Cabinet Office. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He has also advised several governments and international bodies including the Australian, New Zealand and US governments, the European Commission, the United Nations Environment Programme and Food and Agriculture Organisation. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He was, for 6 years, a member of the Natural Environment Research Council. In June 1997 he was awarded the Heidelberg Award for Environmental Excellence, in 2001 he became a Fellow of the Royal Society. In 2004 he was awarded the Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George by Her Majesty the Queen and in June 2010 was awarded a knighthood in the Queen’s Birthday Honours. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Twitter: uksciencechief &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="michael-coughlin-executive-director-local-government-association"&gt;Michael Coughlin: Executive Director, Local Government Association&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Michael is Executive Director at the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.local.gov.uk/"&gt;LGA&lt;/a&gt; having recently been Chief Executive at Reading Unitary Authority, previously serving as Chief Executive at Crawley Borough Council in West Sussex. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He has over 30 years experience of working in local government, having worked in two Director positions at the Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead and prior to that at Elmbridge Borough Council and Bexley London Borough. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This has included extensive work with Councillors of all political parties and at a national level with a variety of Government departments, Ministers and senior Civil Servants. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He is educated to degree level with post-graduate qualifications in Management, Marketing and Leisure. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Responsible for a number of organisational and service programmes, major regeneration and capital projects and behaviour change, innovation and community engagement. He is a judge for both the Municipal Journal and O2 Future Fund. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Michael has served on the South East England Councils, South East Strategic Leaders and Improvement and Efficiency South East’s Chief Executives’ Advisory Groups. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He was a Board member of Thames Valley Connexions and Reading UK Economic Development Company, is an alumni of the Leadership Centre for Local Government’s Leeds Castle programme, and a Fellow of the Royal Society for the Arts. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Michael is married with a family of older youngsters. He is a league and team squash player and plays bass and guitar. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Twitter: m__coughlin &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="john-dodds-director-of-innovation-at-the-department-for-business-innovation-and-skills-head-of-dsb-secretariat"&gt;John Dodds: Director of Innovation at the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, Head of &lt;abbr title="Data Strategy Board"&gt;DSB&lt;/abbr&gt; Secretariat&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;John has been the Director of Innovation at the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills since March 2011. John and his teams work to support Ministers in their objective that Britain should be one of the most innovative economies in the world – with innovation making a major contribution to growth. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;From 2006 to 2011 John was Director of the Better Regulation Executive with the objective of reducing the impact of red tape on business. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Previously, John carried out a broad range of roles in HM Treasury including spells as: &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Head of the Defence, Diplomacy and Intelligence Team (2002-2006), leading Treasury interests in defence spending and procurement &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Head of Information Services (1997-2002), leading the Treasury’s internal information strategy and with responsibility for delivery of IT, library and records management services &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Head of the Budget Coordination Team (1994-1997), project managing the Chancellor of the Exchequer’s Budget for Ken Clarke and Gordon Brown and editor of the Budget ‘Red Book’ &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Policy Adviser in the European Community Division (1991-1994) playing a key role in the negotiation of the 1992 European Community financing settlement and the accession of Sweden, Finland and Austria to the European Union.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;John studied Mathematics at Christ’s College, Cambridge from 1979-1982 and has an MSc in Statistics from Manchester University where he won the M S Bartlett prize in 1983. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="sir-ian-magee-cb-chair-geographic-information-customer-group"&gt;Sir Ian Magee CB: Chair, Geographic Information Customer Group&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ian Magee is Chair of the Geographic Information Customer Group. He is a Senior Fellow of the Institute for Government. He is co-author of ‘Read Before Burning’, the Institute’s report on arms-length bodies (July 2010); of ‘System Error’ the Institute’s report on government IT (March 2011); and of ‘System Upgrade?’ (June 2012), the Institute’s analysis of the progress government is making with its ICT strategy. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Until 2005, he was 2nd Permanent Secretary at the Department for Constitutional Affairs; and Head of Profession for Operational Delivery for the whole Civil Service. He has been a CEO of three different Executive Agencies. Ian was a member of the Capability Review team for the Cabinet Office. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He was a Senior Adviser to Booz and Company, international management consultants, and is an Advisory Board member of two companies. Ian is an Executive Coach to senior civil servants and others. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ian conducted a review of criminality information for the Home Secretary, published in July 2008; and a review of the Legal Services Commission for the Justice Secretary, published in March 2010. Ian has a special interest in public sector leadership, and in the effective use of data to improve services to the public. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="heather-savory-chair-governments-open-data-user-group"&gt;Heather Savory: Chair, Government’s Open Data User Group&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Heather is a successful executive with a solid commercial track-record and extensive board and senior management experience in entrepreneurial and high technology businesses, consulting and central government. She has strong expertise in all aspects of high growth business development and large-scale change environments. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Heather is Chair of the Government’s &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/news/chair-open-data-user-group-appointed"&gt;Open Data User Group (ODUG)&lt;/a&gt;; she also sits as a member of the Public Sector Transparency Board and on the Regulatory Board of the Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors (RICS). &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Previously Heather has worked at 3Dlabs as Vice President of Engineering and Operations, eComData as Managing Director and at the centre of UK Government spending two years in HM Treasury and three in the Department of Business, Innovation and Skills at the Better Regulation Executive (&lt;abbr title="Better Regulation Executive"&gt;BRE&lt;/abbr&gt;). &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Heather graduated from Loughborough University of Technology with a 1st class BSc (Hons) in Electronic and Electrical Engineering and a Diploma in Industrial Studies; she also has an Executive MBA from London Business School. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Twitter: SaturnSA4 &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="steve-thomas-managing-director-for-strategic-development-experian-plc"&gt;Steve Thomas: Managing Director for Strategic Development, Experian Plc&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Steve has been a UK board member since joining Experian in April 2007. He leads Experian’s UK Industry Sector Development and Operations including Public Sector. He is also responsible for UK Strategy, Marketing and Communications. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Steve joined Experian in April 2007 following 18 years at IBM, where he served on the UK board as Vice President of the Communications and Industrial sectors for UK, Ireland and South Africa. Whilst at IBM Steve led a number of multi-billion technology, software and consulting businesses in the UK &amp;amp; EMEA. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Steve graduated from Loughborough University with a BSc (Joint Hons) in Mathematics &amp;amp; Sports Science. He also has gained an IBM Executive Development at Insead and an IBM Condensed MBA from Harvard. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="chris-yiu-head-of-digital-government-unit-the-policy-exchange"&gt;Chris Yiu: Head of Digital Government Unit, the Policy Exchange&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chris Yiu is Head of the Digital Government Unit at Policy Exchange, the UK’s leading think tank. He directs research on public policy for a world increasingly dominated by technology, data and the internet. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chris authored the Policy Exchange report ‘A right to data’, which called for all of the non-personal data collected or created to support the day-to-day business of government to be made open: easy to access and free at the point of delivery, without restriction on use or reuse. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He also authored ‘The big data opportunity’, which dealt with the opportunities and challenges presented by big data and analytics in the public sector. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chris is serving on the Data Strategy Board as a member of the Coalition for a Public Interest Data Policy. This is an independent group interested in the development of public data policies that promote transparency, efficiency and innovation whilst consolidating fundamental rights. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chris has spent the past decade working at the heart of public policy and business strategy. In government he held a number of positions, including advising on tax and financial services policy at HM Treasury, and on economic and foreign policy at the Prime Minister’s Strategy Unit. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In business he served a range of clients with McKinsey &amp;amp; Company, working across the technology, financial services, healthcare and consumer goods sectors. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chris was born and brought up in London. He holds a first class degree in economics and a master’s degree in economics and finance, both from the University of Cambridge. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Twitter: @PXDigitalGov &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="bill-roberts-ceo-swirrl-it-ltd"&gt;Bill Roberts: CEO, Swirrl IT Ltd&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bill Roberts is CEO and co-founder of Swirrl IT Ltd. Swirrl works with public sector organisations to help them share their data as ‘5-star’ linked open data. Recognising that the benefits of open data are only realised when the data is used is the guiding principle of Swirrl’s approach. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bill spends much of his time engaging with re-users of public sector data - in central and local government, the third sector, academics and private sector companies. Bill hopes to bring this hands-on experience of the open data economy to bear on the issues the Data Strategy Board is tasked to address. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bill has a PhD in Fluid Dynamics from the University of Edinburgh. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Twitter: @billroberts &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="overview-of-the-board"&gt;Overview of the Board&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;abbr title="Data Strategy Board"&gt;DSB&lt;/abbr&gt; is a Ministerial Advisory Board that advises &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.bis.gov.uk/ministers/david-willetts"&gt;David Willetts&lt;/a&gt;, Minister for Universities and Science, and &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/content/francis-maude-minister-cabinet-office"&gt;Francis Maude&lt;/a&gt;, Minister of Cabinet Office. It is led by an independent chair, and includes data users from outside the public sector, including representatives of commercial re-users and the Open Data community. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Board also incorporates existing public sector customer groups, who will continue to provide sector expertise around the commissioning of weather services and geographic information for the public sector. The &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/about-us/what/pws/customer-group"&gt;Public Weather Service Customer Group&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.communities.gov.uk/news/corporate/1878453"&gt;Geographic Information Group&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/content/open-data-user-group"&gt;Open Data User Group&lt;/a&gt; will become sub-committees of the &lt;abbr title="Data Strategy Board"&gt;DSB&lt;/abbr&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are 2 to 3 public sector seats for the chair to appoint. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content>
